- fix stroke paths: Marker paths are the biggest risk. Even with RDP, complex strokes can produce 50+ points × 2 floats × 2 coords. That's ~800 bytes per stroke uncompressed. Store at reduced precision (2 decimal places max).

1. Is 70% Confidence Good Enough?
No. Not really — but it's the right starting point for a graceful system.

70% sounds like a passing grade. In practice, it means you're auto-applying restorations where nearly 1 in 3 signals disagrees. For an eraser specifically, that's a dangerous tolerance — a false positive means you silently delete something the user didn't intend to delete on this reload.

The real problem is that the threshold is binary and uniform across wildly different site behaviors:

A static documentation site (MDN, Stripe docs) → virtually zero churn. 70% is overkill.
A news homepage (NYT, Reddit) → DOM restructures on every deploy. 70% is reckless.
A React SPA that dynamically renders based on server state → anchors may be irreproducible.
Site refactoring is brutal. A major redesign can blow out every anchor simultaneously:

IDs get renamed or dropped
XPaths change as layout structure changes
Text content gets reworded, internationalized, or A/B tested
Visual geometry shifts with responsive redesigns
A site like Reddit or Twitter does rolling deployments daily. Your confidence scores could degrade to 30% across the board overnight, and nothing tells the user.

The deeper issue: confidence is a signal about which anchor field survived, not about whether the right element was found. A 90% match that resolves to the wrong element (because a sibling element inherited the same ID after a CMS change) is worse than a 65% match that correctly finds the target. The score is a proxy, not a guarantee.

2. Options for Dealing with Churn
Here are practical strategies, ranked by implementation effort:

A. Domain-Aware Staleness Tracking (low effort, high value) Record the last successful restoration timestamp per domain. If a domain hasn't had a successful restoration in 30 days, badge it as "stale" in the Sites history page. At minimum, you know the data is aging.

B. Re-identification on User Visit (medium effort) When confidence drops below threshold, instead of silently skipping, store a needsReview: true flag. On next visit, surface a subtle floating indicator: "1 edit on this page couldn't be found — tap to review." Let the user either dismiss it (abandon the edit) or re-pin it by clicking the element they meant.

C. The "Snapshot Hash" Strategy (medium effort) At save time, also record a hash of the parent DOM subtree neighborhood (not just the element). On restore, if the anchor resolves but the hash doesn't match, flag it as potentially drifted rather than confident. This adds a secondary sanity check independent of the layered confidence score.

D. Passive Drift Detection (harder) Keep a lightweight record of which anchors restored successfully on the previous visit. On the next visit, compare. If previously-healthy anchors are now failing, the page likely changed. Surface a domain-level warning: "This site may have been redesigned."

E. User-Pinnable Re-anchoring UI (hardest, most trustworthy) The broken anchor review workflow you described in the original product plan but cut: amber highlight + tooltip confirmation. This is the right long-term answer. When anchors fail, show the best candidate in amber and ask the user to confirm or re-select. It respects user intent and builds trust.

The toast notification you added (better than before, as you note) is the right short-term move. The amber re-pinning workflow is where you eventually want to land.

3. Is a Separate Floating UI for Anomalies Worth It?
Yes — but scope it tightly.

A full "Edit Review" panel would be over-engineering for an MVP. But a persistent floating chip (not a toast — toasts disappear) for broken-anchor sessions has real value:

┌─────────────────────────────────┐
│  V  2 edits couldn't be applied │  [Review]  ✕
└─────────────────────────────────┘
Persists until dismissed (unlike a toast)
"Review" opens a modal listing the failed anchors with their last-known description
User can delete stale anchors or attempt to manually re-pin
The human-readable data problem (your ["github.com"].items[19] example) is real. A raw anchor object tells a user nothing. They need something like:

"Erased: sidebar nav element — last seen at github.com/pulls"

That means you need to store at save time:

A short human-readable description (e.g., element.tagName + textContent?.slice(0, 40))
The URL it was applied to
The action type
That description doesn't need to be long. "DIV · Trending repositories" is 26 bytes. At scale across hundreds of edits, this adds maybe 50–200 bytes per item — well within budget. The description field is worth storing. It's the thing that makes the broken-anchor review workflow humane.





