  2. Killing the select tool entirely — bigger, and it has one real obstacle.   
   
  Why clicking-anywhere-to-select isn't free today                              
                  
  Marker wrappers live on top of page content with pointer-events: none         
  (content/marker.js:1321). That's deliberate — a pen stroke scribbled across an
   article paragraph must not block the user from clicking links underneath. The
   select tool "turns on" pointer events only while the mode is active (line
  1322). So "always selectable" means removing that shield, which means a
  freehand stroke over body text steals clicks from the page.

  Stickies and the dock don't hit this because they're solid cards — you already
   don't want to click through them. Paint objects are the hard case, and
  they're the reason the select tool exists as a mode.                          
                  
  The workable path, if you want to pursue this                                 
   
  Keep pointer-events: none on shapes, but run the select handlers              
  unconditionally at the document level (they already use geometric
  isPointNearShape hit-testing, not DOM hit-testing — so wrapper pointer-events 
  don't matter). Then gate "steal this click for selection" on:
  - pointer is within a tight proximity (say 4–6px of the actual stroke path,
  not just the bbox)                                                            
  - AND the element under the pointer is not interactive (a, button, input,
  [contenteditable], form fields)                                               
  - AND no paint tool is currently active (pen/arrow/rect/etc. still own their  
  clicks for drawing)                                                         
                                                                                
  If those hold, select. Otherwise fall through. Stickies and text boxes are
  always selectable since they're opaque anyway. Select tool goes away, dock    
  gets one fewer button.
                                                                                
  Concerns        

  - Drag-to-move on pen mode: if you're drawing and your first pointerdown      
  happens to be 3px from an existing stroke, does it drag or draw? Need the rule
   "active paint tool always wins."                                             
  - Tiny markers: an 8px arrow in the corner of a dense page would fight for
  every click. Proximity threshold needs to scale down for small shapes.        
  - Discoverability of the affordance: without a dedicated mode, how does the
  user know a pen stroke is draggable? Cursor change on hover (already in place 
  for select mode via html.vellum-select-mode) would need to become always-on
  for Vellum elements — which is fine, just more CSS.                           
                  
  My take

  Do (1) this week — it's the inconsistency you're actually running into. Then  
  try (2) behind a one-liner feature flag; if the proximity+interactive-guard
  rule feels good on a dense page like a news article, delete the select tool.  
  If it feels janky (accidental selects on content, fights with page clicks),
  the select tool earned its keep.

